[Student "S"]
{South first transfers you to \Ss, then closes the auction with 4\S. 

North is to play 4\S. East leads the \C2. West takes the \CA and returns the \C9 to East's \CK. East plays another \C to your \CQ. 

With two tricks lost already you have a sure \D loser (unless the defenders goof) and a \H loser that might be taken care of if West holds the \HK. But what if East holds the \HK? Maybe an elimination play.

First pull trumps - they split 2-1.

Next eliminate \Ds by playing \DA then another \D. This does the elimination and throw-in at the same time.

If the defender who won the \DK plays a \D or a \C you will ruff in your hand and discard dummy's \H loser. So that defender is going to have to lead a \H.

If it is East who won the \DK you are home free. His \H play will give you two \H tricks.

If it is West who won the \DK you still have a chance. He will lead a \H and you will finesse the \HQ.

In other words, played this way you make the contract whenever East holds the \DK <b>OR</b> West holds the \HK.

. 

With the cards as shown the elimination play works.

But if the \DK is with West and the \HK with East it wouldn't.

Of course it is POSSIBLE that if you played a low \D from dummy some Easts would duck and let you win a trick with your \DQ. 

This trickery would fail if East held the \DK, or if West held it and went up right away.}
[Play "W"]C2

